"""
MKT Context Commentary — Micah chapters 1–6 (85 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-micah-1-6.py

Micah prophesied ca. 735–700 BCE, contemporary with Isaiah. Rural prophet
from Moresheth-Gath (Judean foothills). Witnessed Samaria's fall (722 BCE)
and Sennacherib's invasion (701 BCE). His social-justice oracles defend the
peasant farmer against the Jerusalem elite. His 3:12 oracle (Jerusalem will
be plowed) was so striking it was cited as precedent for Jeremiah's defense
a century later (Jer 26:18-19).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MICAH = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>Micah's superscription places him in the reigns of Jotham, Ahaz, and Hezekiah (ca. 735–700 BCE), contemporary with Isaiah (Isa 1:1) and overlapping with the earlier ministry of Hosea and Amos. His hometown, <em>Moresheth</em> (Moresheth-Gath), was a village in the Shephelah — the agricultural lowland between the coastal plain and the Judean hills, about 35 km southwest of Jerusalem. His rural, non-capital perspective shapes his entire prophetic message: he speaks not from the palace or the temple but from the farming communities that bore the economic weight of both Samaria and Jerusalem.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Hear, all you peoples; pay attention, O earth, and all that is in it' — the summons to a cosmic court. Micah opens with a call that encompasses the entire earth as witness, not just Israel and Judah. YHWH comes forth from his place (his heavenly temple) and will tread upon the high places of the earth — a theophanic image closely paralleling Amos 4:13 ('he who treads on the heights of the earth') and Deut 33:29. The calling of the earth as witness to YHWH's case against his own people follows the pattern of Deut 32:1 (Moses' Song) and Isa 1:2.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'For behold, YHWH is coming out of his place and will come down and tread upon the high places of the earth.' The language of divine descent for judgment is common in theophany texts (Gen 11:5, 18:21; Exod 3:8; Ps 144:5). The 'high places' (<em>bamot</em>) are both literal mountain summits and the cultic high places where illicit worship occurred — YHWH's theophanic tread will shatter both geography and false cult simultaneously.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The mountains melt like wax before fire; the valleys split open. This volcanic and seismic imagery is theophanic (cf. Ps 97:5; Nah 1:5; Judg 5:5 — the Sinai tradition of YHWH causing mountains to melt). The imagery deliberately recalls Sinai-style divine presence: YHWH is approaching his people with the same power that established the covenant — but now to execute its curses rather than establish its promises.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'All this is for the transgression of Jacob and for the sins of the house of Israel.' The twofold designation — transgression of Jacob / sin of house of Israel — encompasses the whole covenant people. But immediately Micah narrows the blame to leadership centers: 'What is the transgression of Jacob? Is it not Samaria? And what is the high place of Judah? Is it not Jerusalem?' Samaria (northern capital) and Jerusalem (southern capital) are named as the sources of corruption that contaminate the whole land — a prophet from the rural fringe indicting both urban centers.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Samaria's punishment is announced: she will become a heap of ruins in the open country and a planting of vineyards. Samaria was indeed destroyed by Sargon II of Assyria in 722 BCE (2 Kgs 17:5-6). The archaeological record confirms Samaria's destruction and depopulation. Micah's prophecy here is the most direct announcement of the northern capital's fate in the pre-722 prophetic corpus. 'Her stones into the valley' and 'her foundations laid bare' describe systematic demolition.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Samaria's 'gathered wages' are destroyed — Micah describes Samaria's wealth as the wages of a prostitute (<em>etnan zonah</em>), money given for cultic prostitution that fed the temple treasury. The money gathered in harlotry will return to hire new prostitutes: the corrupt wealth cycle continues even in destruction. 'All her images will be beaten to pieces, all her idols burned with fire': the language of Deuteronomic reform (Deut 7:5, 25). This will be 'gathered from the wages of a prostitute, and to the wages of a prostitute they shall return' — a grim economic irony.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Micah's personal lamentation shifts the oracle from third person announcement to first person mourning: 'For this I will lament and wail; I will go stripped and naked; I will make lamentation like the jackals, and mourning like the ostriches.' The prophet's stripping himself and wailing like a jackal or ostrich (known for eerie nocturnal cries) was a recognized form of public prophetic mourning that dramatized the oracle. This performance of grief authenticates the prophet's sorrow as genuine rather than detached.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'For her wound is incurable, and it has come to Judah; it has reached to the gate of my people, to Jerusalem.' Samaria's corruption is not contained — it has spread south to Judah and reached Jerusalem's very gates. The 'wound' (<em>makkah</em>) is used of plague or military defeat; its incurable character (<em>anushit</em>) echoes Jer 15:18 (Jeremiah's own 'incurable wound'). Micah introduces the contagion model: Samaria's sin is infectious, spreading south.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Micah's famous wordplay lament: 'Tell it not in Gath' — echoing David's lament over Saul (2 Sam 1:20 'tell it not in Gath'). The passage continues with a series of town-name puns in the Shephelah region — Micah's home territory. <em>Gath / tagidu</em> (tell), <em>Beth-le-aphrah / aphar</em> (dust, 'in Beth of Dust, roll in the dust'), etc. These are the towns of Micah's homeland, and each receives a wordplay oracle about its own judgment. The lament is hyper-local: Micah is not prophesying abstractly but about the specific towns he grew up near.</p>",
    "11": "<p><em>Shaphir</em> — wordplay on <em>shaphar</em> (beautiful): 'Pass on your way, inhabitant of Shaphir [Beautiful], in nakedness and shame.' <em>Zaanan</em> — 'does not come out' (wordplay on <em>yatza</em>). <em>Beth-ezel</em> — 'its standing place is taken away' (wordplay on <em>etzel</em>). The sequence of villages and their wordplays creates a rapid-fire lamentation that reads like a litany of local grief. Each village name becomes a caption for its own disaster.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>Maroth</em> — 'the inhabitant of Maroth writhes in pain' (wordplay on <em>marah</em>, bitter, or <em>mar</em>, pain). 'For disaster has come down from YHWH to the gate of Jerusalem.' The oracle swings back from the Shephelah towns to the ultimate target: the disaster sweeping through Micah's home region is en route to Jerusalem. The series of town puns serves as a geographic trail marking the Assyrian advance south toward the capital.</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>Lachish</em> — 'harness the steeds to the chariots, inhabitant of Lachish.' Lachish was the most significant fortified city in the Judean Shephelah and a major Assyrian military target. Sennacherib's assault on Lachish (701 BCE) was commemorated in famous palace reliefs (now in the British Museum). Micah accuses Lachish of being the 'beginning of sin to the daughter of Zion' — implying that Lachish was where the cavalry-and-chariot military culture that replaced trust in YHWH entered Judah (cf. Deut 17:16; Isa 31:1-3).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Moresheth-Gath — Micah's own hometown — receives a farewell oracle: 'Therefore you shall give parting gifts to Moresheth-Gath.' The Hebrew <em>shiluchim</em> (parting gifts / divorce settlement) is exactly the dowry paid when a bride leaves her father's house, or the payment given when a wife is divorced. Moresheth-Gath will be given up — Israel is divorcing its own land. <em>Achzib</em> — 'a lie to the kings of Israel' (wordplay on <em>achziv</em>, lie/disappointment) — a town name punning on its destiny as false hope.</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>Mareshah</em> — 'I will again bring a conqueror to you' (wordplay on <em>yoresh</em>, conqueror/heir). 'The glory of Israel shall come to Adullam' — Adullam was the cave where David fled from Saul (1 Sam 22:1), a place of refuge and royal exile. Micah ironically inverts this: Israel's glory (its nobles, its leadership) will flee there as refugees, as David once did. The phrase 'glory of Israel' (<em>kevod Yisrael</em>) is deliberately degraded by its destination — a cave of exile.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Make yourselves bald and cut off your hair, for the children of your delight; make yourselves as bald as the eagle, for they shall go from you into exile.' Shaving the head was a standard mourning practice in the ancient Near East (cf. Amos 8:10; Isa 22:12; Job 1:20). The 'eagle' (<em>nesher</em>) — likely the griffon vulture, whose bald head was a recognizable sight — provides the vivid comparison. Ch. 1 ends with the image of Judah's mothers mourning children deported into Assyrian exile.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>'Woe to those who devise wickedness and work evil on their beds! When the morning dawns, they carry it out, because it is in the power of their hand.' The opening oracle of ch. 2 identifies the social enemy: the powerful landowner who plans land seizures at night and executes them by day. The nighttime planning echoes Ps 4:4 ('meditate in your hearts upon your beds') inverted: they meditate on injustice rather than on YHWH. The power to execute the plan immediately (<em>ki yesh-le'el yadam</em>, 'for it is in the power of their hand') is itself identified as dangerous — wealth that translates instantly into legal and physical coercion.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'They covet fields and seize them, and houses, and take them away; they oppress a man and his house, a man and his inheritance (<em>nachalah</em>).' The verb <em>chamad</em> (covet) directly cites the tenth commandment (Exod 20:17; Deut 5:21). This is the Decalogue applied to land theft. The word <em>nachalah</em> (inheritance/ancestral allotment) is theologically loaded: in Israel's land theology, the tribal allotments were YHWH's gift held in trust for family lines — they could not be permanently sold away (Lev 25; cf. Naboth's vineyard, 1 Kgs 21). Seizing a man's <em>nachalah</em> is both economic crime and theological violation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Therefore thus says YHWH: behold, against this family I am devising disaster.' YHWH counters the nighttime evil-devising with his own counter-devise (<em>choschev</em>) — using the exact same verb. The disaster from which they cannot escape or remove their necks will humble their proud gait. The 'family' (<em>mishpachah</em>) targeted may refer to the ruling class as a whole or specifically to the northern dynasty.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'In that day they shall take up a taunt against you and moan bitterly, and say, &ldquo;We are utterly ruined; he changes the portion of my people; how he removes it from me! To an apostate he allots our fields.&rdquo;' The lamentation they will utter over themselves anticipates the reversal: the land-grabbers will be lamented over by themselves as their own lands are redistributed. 'To an apostate he allots our fields' — the Assyrian conqueror (or divine judgment acting through him) will redistribute their ill-gotten estates.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Therefore you will have none to cast the line by lot in the assembly of YHWH.' The casting of the line (<em>chevel begoral</em>) refers to the measurement cord used in land allotment (cf. Josh 17:5; Ps 16:6). The punishment mirrors the crime: those who stole others' measured allotments will have no one to measure out land for them in the coming restoration. They are excluded from the eschatological re-distribution of the land.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Do not preach' — thus they preach — 'one should not preach of such things; disgrace will not overtake us.' The false prophets and their patrons silence Micah: 'Don't prophesy!' (<em>al-tatifun</em>). The word <em>nataf</em> (drip/prophesy) is used in Amos 7:16 similarly. The self-exemption from disgrace ('disgrace will not overtake us') is the standard psychology of those who believe their social power protects them from divine accountability. Micah has been suppressed — he reports their suppression.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Should this be said, O house of Jacob? Has the Spirit of YHWH grown impatient? Are these his deeds? Do not my words do good to him who walks uprightly?' Micah turns the false prophets' theology against them. If YHWH's words are only comfort and the land-grabbers are comfortable, then YHWH's Spirit has run out of patience for justice. But YHWH's words do good to those who walk uprightly — implying that those who hear only good news from their prophets are not walking uprightly.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'But lately my people have risen up as an enemy; you strip the rich robe from those who pass by trustingly, like men returning from war.' The social violence is described vividly: ordinary people (perhaps creditors or land-seizing nobles) strip the outer cloak (<em>aderet</em>) from passersby — the very act prohibited in Exod 22:26 (a creditor may not keep a poor man's cloak overnight). 'Like men returning from war' — those who expect to be safe, returning home, are instead attacked by their own countrymen.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'The women of my people you drive out from their pleasant houses; from their young children you take away my splendor forever.' Women (widows or wives) are evicted from their homes. The children lose their glory (<em>hadar</em>) — their inheritance, their social dignity, their future. 'Forever' (<em>le'olam</em>): Micah emphasizes the permanence of the damage done to children by landlessness. This is generational poverty built into the social structure.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Arise and go, for this is no place to rest, because of uncleanness that destroys with grievous destruction.' The land itself vomits out the unclean. The language echoes Lev 18:25-28: the land vomits out its inhabitants for their wickedness. This is the land's own sacred ecology — a concept unique to Israel's theology where the land is not morally neutral but responds to the behavior of its inhabitants.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'If a man should go about in a spirit of falsehood and lie, saying, &ldquo;I will preach to you of wine and strong drink,&rdquo; he would be the preacher for this people!' The bitter irony: the land-grabbing elite want a prophet who will prophesy them wine and beer rather than judgment. Micah identifies the market for false prophecy: not spiritual error but economic convenience. A prophet who tells powerful people what they want to hear has a reliable patron base — and no shortage of clients.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Micah inserts a restoration oracle into the midst of judgment: 'I will surely assemble all of you, O Jacob; I will gather the remnant of Israel; I will set them together like sheep in a fold, like a flock in its pasture, a noisy multitude of men.' The sudden shift to salvation — typical of the prophetic alternation of judgment and hope — names the coming gathering of a remnant (<em>she'erit Yisrael</em>). The metaphor of the noisy flock packed into a fold contrasts with the scattered exile of judgment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'He who opens the breach goes up before them; they break through and pass the gate, going out by it. Their king passes on before them, YHWH at their head.' The 'breach-breaker' (<em>poretz</em>) who leads the flock is a royal/messianic figure. The image is of a shepherd breaking down a pen wall to lead sheep out — the same metaphor that appears in John 10:3 (the shepherd calls his own and leads them out). YHWH himself goes at the head of this procession, the exodus-restoration merger of leadership that characterizes Micah's eschatology.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>'And I said: Hear, you heads of Jacob and rulers of the house of Israel! Is it not for you to know justice?' Micah directly addresses the political leadership — the <em>roshei Ya'akov</em> (heads of Jacob) and <em>qetzinei beit Yisrael</em> (rulers of Israel). These are the judges, elders, and tribal leaders whose primary responsibility is the administration of justice (<em>mishpat</em>). Micah's charge is not economic complaint but legal dereliction: those appointed to know justice have abandoned it.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'You who hate the good and love the evil, who tear the skin from off my people and their flesh from off their bones.' The inversion of good and evil — hating what should be loved, loving what should be hated — is the fundamental moral disorder. The predatory imagery of flaying skin from bones is extreme and deliberate: Micah wants to shock his audience into recognizing the violence in what looks like ordinary legal and economic activity. 'Tearing skin from bone' describes judicial and economic extraction that leaves people stripped of everything.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Who eat the flesh of my people, and flay their skin from off them, and break their bones in pieces and chop them up like meat in a pot, like flesh in a cauldron.' The extended cannibal butchery metaphor continues. The cooking pot and cauldron were everyday domestic objects — Micah transforms them into images of the elite consuming the poor. The phrase 'flesh of my people' (<em>she'er ammi</em>) is used throughout: the rulers feed on YHWH's own covenant people.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Then they will cry to YHWH, but he will not answer them; he will hide his face from them at that time, because they have made their deeds evil.' The hiding of YHWH's face (<em>yaster panav mehem</em>) is the covenant curse of abandonment (Deut 31:17-18; Ps 13:1; Isa 59:2). The leadership that provided no justice in the courts will receive no justice from the divine court — their cry will be answered with silence. The retributive symmetry is precise.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Thus says YHWH concerning the prophets who lead my people astray, who cry &ldquo;Peace&rdquo; when they have something to eat, but declare war against him who puts nothing in their mouths.' The false prophets operate on a pay-for-prophecy model: feed them and they prophesy <em>shalom</em> (peace); withhold their fee and they declare holy war (<em>qiddeshu milchamah</em>) against you. This is the commercialization of prophecy that Micah condemns throughout — oracular output determined by economic incentive rather than divine mandate.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Therefore it shall be night to you, without vision, and darkness to you, without divination. The sun shall go down on the prophets, and the day shall be black over them.' The solar imagery is ironic: prophets are those who receive divine light/vision; their punishment is divine darkness — the withdrawal of the prophetic gift. The 'going down of the sun' on the prophets may also glance at Amos 8:9 ('I will make the sun go down at noon') as a shared Day-of-the-LORD image.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'The seers shall be disgraced, and the diviners put to shame; they shall all cover their lips, for there is no answer from God.' 'Covering the lips' (<em>atam al-saphah</em>) was the gesture of a leper announcing his uncleanness (Lev 13:45) or of mourning (Ezek 24:17). The false prophets will be publicly shamed: their mouths, which spoke purchased prophecies, will be covered in shame before the absence of authentic divine speech. The contrast with Micah himself (v. 8) is direct.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'But as for me, I am filled with power, with the Spirit of YHWH, and with justice and might, to declare to Jacob his transgression and to Israel his sin.' Micah's counter-claim to the false prophets: he speaks by the Spirit of YHWH, not for hire. The triple endowment — <em>koach</em> (power), <em>mishpat</em> (justice/judgment), <em>gevurah</em> (might) — contrasts with the darkness and shame decreed for the fee-prophets. His function is unambiguous: to 'declare to Jacob his transgression' — the very thing the false prophets refused to do.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Hear this, you heads of the house of Jacob and rulers of the house of Israel, who detest justice and make crooked all that is straight.' The final oracle of ch. 3 addresses all three corrupt groups together: rulers (vv. 9-10), priests (v. 11), and prophets (v. 11). They 'detest justice' (<em>mete'avim mishpat</em>) and make crooked what is straight (<em>ha'et hayyeshaw ye'aqqeshu</em>) — the exact inverse of their calling. Ps 9:7-8 and Isa 5:20 use similar language of good-evil inversion.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Who build Zion with blood and Jerusalem with iniquity.' The building of Jerusalem with blood (<em>bedamim</em>) echoes Hab 2:12 ('woe to him who builds a town with blood'). The magnificent building projects that adorned the capital city — the monuments of Israelite civilization — are built on systemic injustice and exploitation. The architecture that symbolizes the covenant people's prosperity is indicted as evidence of their crime.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Its heads give judgment for a bribe; its priests teach for a price; its prophets practice divination for money; yet they lean on YHWH and say, &ldquo;Is not YHWH in the midst of us? No disaster shall come upon us.&rdquo;' The three corrupt offices (judiciary, priesthood, prophecy) are all monetized. Most devastating: they invoke YHWH's presence as their security guarantee — the temple theology that says YHWH dwelling in Zion makes Jerusalem inviolable. This is the theology Jeremiah will combat in his famous Temple Sermon (Jer 7:4: 'the temple of YHWH, the temple of YHWH, the temple of YHWH').</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Therefore because of you Zion shall be plowed as a field; Jerusalem shall become a heap of ruins, and the mountain of the house a wooded height.' Micah 3:12 is the most explicit announcement of Jerusalem's destruction in the pre-exilic prophets. So striking was this oracle that it was cited verbatim a century later as a precedent in Jeremiah's trial (Jer 26:18-19): Hezekiah did not execute Micah for saying this; therefore Jeremiah should not be executed either. The text thus provides rare biblical evidence for the citation and preservation of earlier prophetic tradition in legal/political debate.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>'It shall come to pass in the latter days that the mountain of the house of YHWH shall be established as the highest of the mountains, and it shall be lifted up above the hills; and peoples shall flow to it.' Micah 4:1-3 is nearly identical to Isa 2:2-4 — two prophets who were contemporaries share (or one copies) the same eschatological vision. The question of priority is debated; both passages may draw from a common liturgical tradition. The vision of Zion exalted to cosmic mountain status, attracting all nations, directly reverses 3:12 (Zion plowed as a field).</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Many nations shall come, and say: &ldquo;Come, let us go up to the mountain of YHWH, to the house of the God of Jacob, that he may teach us his ways and that we may walk in his paths.&rdquo; For out of Zion shall go forth the law, and the word of YHWH from Jerusalem.' The Gentile pilgrimage to Zion for Torah instruction reverses the missionary situation of Jonah: here the nations come to Israel for YHWH's teaching. The 'law' (<em>torah</em>) going forth from Zion is the governing instruction for the new world order, replacing the Assyrian imperial law that goes forth from Nineveh.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'He shall judge between many peoples, and shall decide disputes for strong nations far away; and they shall beat their swords into plowshares, and their spears into pruning hooks; nation shall not lift up sword against nation, neither shall they learn war anymore.' The universal disarmament oracle: the instruments of war are recycled into agricultural implements. YHWH as arbiter replaces international war. The oracle's famous reversal in Joel 3:10 ('beat your plowshares into swords') does not contradict Micah — Joel addresses the pre-judgment assembly of enemies, Micah the post-judgment era of peace.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'But they shall sit every man under his vine and under his fig tree, and no one shall make them afraid, for the mouth of YHWH of hosts has spoken.' The vine-and-fig-tree image of peaceful domestic security appears in 1 Kgs 4:25 (Solomon's kingdom: 'each man under his vine and his fig tree') and becomes a standard eschatological image (Zech 3:10). Micah's choice is pointed: the peasants stripped of their vineyards and fields in ch. 2 will in the end sit securely under their own. The promise answers the crime directly.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'For all the peoples walk each in the name of its god, but we will walk in the name of YHWH our God forever and ever.' The affirmation of Israelite exclusive loyalty to YHWH in the context of admitting that other peoples walk in their own gods' names. This is not theological pluralism — YHWH will judge the nations (v. 3) — but a statement of present reality: each nation currently follows its own deity. Israel's response is commitment: <em>anachnu</em> (we, emphatic) will walk in YHWH's name.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'In that day, declares YHWH, I will assemble the lame and gather those who have been driven away and those whom I have afflicted.' The gathering of the exiles is described with three groups: the lame (<em>hatzolea</em>), the driven-away (<em>hanidachah</em>), and those YHWH himself has afflicted (<em>asher hare'oti</em>). The third group is remarkable: YHWH claims authorship of the suffering that drove the people into exile. This is honest theodicy — suffering is not random but purposeful, even if painful.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'And the lame I will make the remnant, and those who were cast off, a strong nation; and YHWH will reign over them in Mount Zion from this time forth and forevermore.' The paradox of divine reversal: the weak become the remnant, the cast-off become the strong nation. The remnant (<em>she'erit</em>) is a key Micah concept (2:12; 4:7; 5:7-8; 7:18) — YHWH's preserved core through judgment. Mount Zion, plowed under in 3:12, here becomes the seat of eternal divine kingship.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'And you, O tower of the flock, hill of the daughter of Zion, to you shall it come, the former dominion shall come, kingship for the daughter of Jerusalem.' The 'tower of the flock' (<em>migdal-eder</em>) is a shepherd's watchtower — evoking the Bethlehem imagery of ch. 5 and the Davidic shepherd-king. The 'former dominion' (<em>mamlachah harishonah</em>) refers to the Davidic kingdom at its height under David and Solomon — its restoration is the messianic expectation that ch. 5 will elaborate.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Now why do you cry aloud? Is there no king in you? Has your counselor perished, that pain seized you like a woman in labor?' The questions address the present crisis (likely the Assyrian advance or the Babylonian exile, depending on redactional history). The mockery — 'is there no king?' — cuts deep: Israel's king had failed to provide the security for which monarchy was instituted (1 Sam 8:20). The birth-pang image will be the vehicle for the restoration oracle of ch. 5.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Writhe and groan, O daughter of Zion, like a woman in labor, for now you shall go out from the city and dwell in the open country; you shall go to Babylon. There you shall be rescued; there YHWH will redeem you from the hand of your enemies.' Micah specifically names Babylon — remarkable if this is pre-exilic (Micah's Assyrian context precedes the Babylonian empire). This either represents genuine predictive prophecy or a later supplement. The mention of Babylon in the context of exile and redemption anticipates the Deutero-Isaianic theme of Babylon as the place of exile from which YHWH will redeem.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Now many nations are assembled against you, saying, &ldquo;Let her be defiled, and let our eyes gaze upon Zion.&rdquo;' The nations' assault on Zion and their desire to witness her defilement and defeat. The language of 'defilement' (<em>techenaf</em>) applied to Zion picks up the land-defilement theology of Lev 18 — the nations see this as the moment to witness the humiliation of YHWH's people.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'But they do not know the thoughts of YHWH; they do not understand his plan, that he has gathered them as sheaves to the threshing floor.' The nations' assault on Zion is unwittingly part of YHWH's plan — they are gathered like sheaves for the threshing. The threshing-floor image appears in Isa 21:10 and is a standard divine-judgment agricultural metaphor: the nations are the grain; Zion is the threshing floor; YHWH is the thresher.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Arise and thresh, O daughter of Zion, for I will make your horn iron, and I will make your hoofs bronze; you shall beat in pieces many peoples; and shall devote their gain to YHWH, their wealth to the Lord of the whole earth.' Zion becomes the threshing ox — iron horns and bronze hooves — crushing the nations. The 'devoting' (<em>hacharem</em>) of spoil to YHWH echoes the herem (holy war) tradition of Joshua. The oracle swings from Zion's weakness (vv. 9-11) to her invincibility under divine empowerment — the classic rescue-of-the-besieged pattern.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>'Now muster your troops, O daughter of troops; siege is laid against us; with a rod they strike the judge of Israel on the cheek.' The verse describes the present siege crisis — the humiliation of Israel's judge (king) being struck on the cheek. The 'striking on the cheek' was a gesture of supreme contempt and legal degradation in the ancient Near East (cf. 1 Kgs 22:24; Job 16:10). Against this backdrop of royal humiliation, the announcement of a new shepherd-king from Bethlehem (v. 2) is all the more dramatic.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'But you, O Bethlehem Ephrathah, who are too little to be among the clans of Judah, from you shall come forth for me one who is to be ruler in Israel, whose coming forth is from of old, from ancient days.' The most famous verse in Micah: the birthplace of the coming ruler. <em>Beit-Lechem Efrata</em> distinguishes this Bethlehem from another in Zebulun (Josh 19:15). 'Too little among the clans of Judah' (<em>tzair lihyot be'alfei Yehudah</em>) — not a large tribal center but a village. Yet from this small Davidic hometown the ruler will come — inverting human expectations of where power originates. <em>Motza'otav mikedem miyemei olam</em> ('whose going forth is from of old, from ancient days') is cited in the NT for the pre-existence of Christ (Matt 2:6; John 7:42).</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Therefore he shall give them up until the time when she who is in labor has given birth; then the rest of his brothers shall return to the people of Israel.' The interim period before the ruler's coming — Israel in labor pains. The woman in labor connects back to 4:9-10 (daughter Zion writhing in labor). The period of exile or occupation is the gestation before the messianic birth. 'The rest of his brothers shall return' — a diaspora-gathering associated with the messianic advent.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'And he shall stand and shepherd his flock in the strength of YHWH, in the majesty of the name of YHWH his God. And they shall dwell secure, for now he shall be great to the ends of the earth.' The coming ruler is a shepherd (<em>ra'ah</em>) — the primary royal metaphor in the ancient Near East and Israel. His strength is YHWH's strength; his majesty is YHWH's name — he rules by divine authorization, not his own power. His greatness extends 'to the ends of the earth' (<em>ad-afsei aretz</em>) — universal scope that goes beyond David's historical kingdom.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'And he shall be their peace. When the Assyrian comes into our land and treads in our palaces, we will raise against him seven shepherds and eight princes of men.' 'He shall be their peace' (<em>vehayah zeh shalom</em>) — the ruler himself, not just his rule, is <em>shalom</em>. The 'seven shepherds and eight princes' is a numerical saying (x / x+1 pattern common in Hebrew wisdom poetry: Prov 6:16, Amos 1:3) indicating sufficiency — enough military leadership to repel any enemy. The immediate application is anti-Assyrian, but the ruler-as-peace principle transcends the historical referent.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'They shall shepherd the land of Assyria with the sword, and the land of Nimrod at its entrances; and he shall deliver us from the Assyrian when he comes into our land and treads within our border.' Assyria/Nimrod (Babylon — see Gen 10:8-12; Nimrod's cities include Nineveh and Babel) are the specific imperial enemies. The coming ruler will reverse the threat: instead of Assyria threatening Israel, Israel's shepherds will shepherd Assyria. The oracle operates on two levels — historical (8th-century Assyrian crisis) and eschatological (permanent defeat of all imperial enemies).</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Then the remnant of Jacob shall be in the midst of many peoples like dew from YHWH, like showers on the grass, which delay not for a man nor wait for the children of man.' The remnant as blessing to the nations — like dew and rain that come not by human effort but by YHWH's provision. The dew simile appears in Ps 133:3 (fraternal unity) and Gen 27:28 (Isaac's blessing for Jacob). The remnant is not merely preserved Israel but a life-giving presence among the nations — a second reading of the Abrahamic 'blessing to all nations' promise (Gen 12:3).</p>",
    "8": "<p>'And the remnant of Jacob shall be among the nations, in the midst of many peoples, like a lion among the beasts of the forest, like a young lion among the flocks of sheep, which, when it goes through, treads down and tears in pieces, and there is none to deliver.' The same remnant described in v. 7 as gentle dew is now a lion among the nations. The two images are complementary: blessing to those who receive the remnant, judgment to those who oppose it. The lion imagery is messianic in Gen 49:9 (Judah as lion's cub).</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Your hand shall be lifted up over your adversaries, and all your enemies shall be cut off.' The warfare oracle continues — Israel's hand lifted over enemies. This is the covenant-victory blessing of Deut 28:1, 7. The oracle moves from the lion image to direct address of the remnant/Israel, assuring them of ultimate military reversal over all enemies.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'And in that day, declares YHWH, I will cut off your horses from among you and will destroy your chariots.' YHWH's purification of Israel begins with its military hardware — horses and chariots. This is the Deuteronomic prohibition applied eschatologically: Deut 17:16 explicitly forbids the Israelite king from multiplying horses, and Isa 31:1-3 condemns reliance on Egyptian cavalry. The coming kingdom will be secured by YHWH's power, not military technology.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'And I will cut off the cities of your land and throw down all your strongholds.' The fortified cities — symbols of military self-reliance and also centers of the socioeconomic injustice Micah condemns — will be removed. The purification removes both military (v. 10-11) and cultic (vv. 12-14) sources of false security and idolatry.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'And I will cut off sorceries from your hand, and you shall have no more tellers of fortunes.' Divination and sorcery (<em>keshafim</em>, <em>me'onautim</em>) are Deuteronomic abominations (Deut 18:10-12) — the attempt to control the future through magical means rather than trusting YHWH. The eschatological purification eliminates the spiritual adultery alongside the physical idolatry. True peace requires purity.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'And I will cut off your carved images and your pillars from among you, and you shall bow down no more to the work of your hands.' Sacred standing stones (<em>matsevot</em>) were originally acceptable worship markers (Gen 28:18; 31:45) but became associated with Baalism and were repeatedly condemned in the reform texts (2 Kgs 3:2; 10:27). Their elimination in the coming age removes the temptation to worship created things over the Creator.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'And I will root out your Asherah poles from among you and destroy your cities.' The Asherah poles were wooden cult symbols associated with the Canaanite mother goddess, condemned throughout the Deuteronomic reform literature (1 Kgs 14:15; 2 Kgs 21:3; 23:6). Their removal completes the purification of the land. 'Destroy your cities' — literally 'your enemies' in some textual traditions — may refer to enemy cities or, following some manuscripts, the cities of the idolatrous.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'And in anger and wrath I will execute vengeance on the nations that did not obey.' The purification of Israel (vv. 10-14) is paralleled by judgment on the disobedient nations. The balance of ch. 5: the remnant will be both blessing (v. 7) and judgment (v. 8-9) among the nations; YHWH will purify his own people while executing vengeance on those who rejected him. The chapter ends with YHWH's wrath as boundary on the universal reign of peace described at the chapter's opening.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>'Hear what YHWH says: Arise, plead your case before the mountains, and let the hills hear your voice.' Micah 6 opens the great covenant lawsuit (<em>rib</em>) of YHWH against Israel. The mountains and hills are summoned as cosmic witnesses — an ancient Near Eastern legal convention in which enduring natural features serve as witnesses to covenant agreements (cf. Josh 24:27; Deut 32:1; Isa 1:2). The genre is the <em>rib</em> pattern: plaintiff (YHWH), defendant (Israel), witnesses (creation), and charges.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Hear, you mountains, the indictment of YHWH, and you enduring foundations of the earth, for YHWH has an indictment against his people, and he will contend with Israel.' The 'enduring foundations' (<em>mosadet aretz</em>) are the permanent geological structures that predate Israel and will outlast it — reliable witnesses precisely because they cannot be bribed or intimidated. YHWH's indictment (<em>rib</em>) is legal: he is bringing suit against his covenant partner.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'O my people, what have I done to you? How have I wearied you? Answer me.' The divine plaintiff questions the defendant with unexpected gentleness: not accusation but genuine inquiry. 'What have I done to you? How have I wearied you?' presupposes that Israel has some grievance. This is pastoral cross-examination, not thunder. YHWH opens by inviting Israel to articulate its complaint — an extraordinary gesture in the ancient Near Eastern context of divine overlords who did not typically seek consent from vassals.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'For I brought you up from the land of Egypt and redeemed you from the house of slavery, and I sent before you Moses, Aaron, and Miriam.' The covenant resume: YHWH's saving acts that ground the covenant relationship. Exodus, redemption, leadership — the three leadership figures (Moses, Aaron, Miriam) reflect an inclusive tradition. Miriam's inclusion as co-leader alongside Moses and Aaron is notable and relatively rare in prophetic recitations of saving history (cf. Exod 15:20-21; Num 12).</p>",
    "5": "<p>'O my people, remember what Balak king of Moab devised, and what Balaam the son of Beor answered him, and what happened from Shittim to Gilgal, that you may know the righteous acts of YHWH.' The Balaam episode (Num 22-24) is recalled: a pagan king hired a prophet to curse Israel; YHWH turned the curse to blessing. Shittim to Gilgal traces the final stages of the wilderness journey — the crossing of the Jordan (Josh 3-4). These specific saving acts are YHWH's evidence that he has been faithful. 'Righteous acts of YHWH' (<em>tzidqot YHWH</em>) — his faithfulness to covenant commitments.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'With what shall I come before YHWH, and bow myself before God on high? Shall I come before him with burnt offerings, with calves a year old?' An anonymous voice responds to YHWH's covenant recitation with the worshiper's anxious question: what offering is sufficient? The escalating sacrifice sequence — calves, thousands of rams, oil, firstborn son — is designed to lead the audience to the reductio ad absurdum of ritual atonement logic. No offering, however extravagant, can substitute for covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Will YHWH be pleased with thousands of rams, with ten thousands of rivers of oil? Shall I give my firstborn for my transgression, the fruit of my body for the sin of my soul?' The rhetoric accelerates to the extreme: child sacrifice. This was practiced by some in the ancient Near East (including, the text indicates, by some Israelites — 2 Kgs 16:3; 21:6; Jer 7:31; 19:5). Micah does not accept it as a live option — the question leads to no. No quantity of sacrifice, however enormous, addresses the actual problem: justice, loyalty, humility.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'He has told you, O man, what is good; and what does YHWH require of you but to do justice, and to love kindness, and to walk humbly with your God?' The most famous verse in Micah — and among the most quoted in the Hebrew Bible — crystallizes the prophetic critique. The answer to v. 6-7's liturgical anxiety is not a new or better sacrifice but three practices already commanded: <em>mishpat</em> (justice — in legal and social life), <em>chesed</em> (covenant faithfulness/kindness — loyalty in relationships), and <em>hatzne'a lechet im-Elohecha</em> (humble walking with God — personal relationship). These are not new revelations; 'he has told you' (<em>higid lecha</em>) — the Torah already communicated this. The problem is obedience, not information.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'The voice of YHWH cries to the city — and it is sound wisdom to fear your name: &ldquo;Hear of the rod and of him who appointed it!&rdquo;' The city addressed is likely Jerusalem or Samaria. The 'rod' (<em>shevet</em>) is the instrument of divine punishment — the Assyrian army as YHWH's rod (Isa 10:5 uses the same metaphor). Sound wisdom (<em>tushiyah</em>) recognizes that fearing YHWH's name is the response to the prophetic warning. The call to hear is addressed to whoever has ears — the crowd assembled at the city gate.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Can I forget any longer the treasures of wickedness in the house of the wicked, and the scant measure that is accursed?' The rhetorical question implies the answer: YHWH cannot overlook the fraudulent commerce that permeates the city. The 'scant measure' (<em>ephah razah</em>, lean/short ephah) refers to the underweight measure used in retail trade — the dishonest merchant giving less than the customer paid for. This specific crime connects to Amos 8:5 (also condemning fraudulent measures) and Lev 19:35-36 (prohibiting dishonest weights).</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Shall I acquit the man with wicked scales and with a bag of deceitful weights?' YHWH continues the court proceedings: the fraudulent scale and the deceitful weights bag are standard images of commercial dishonesty in the ancient Near East (cf. Prov 11:1; 16:11; 20:10, 23; Hos 12:7; Amos 8:5). The expected answer is no — YHWH will not acquit (<em>ezke</em>) commercial fraud. The scales of divine justice weigh accurately what the commercial scales of the corrupt city do not.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'Your rich men are full of violence; your inhabitants speak lies, and their tongue is deceitful in their mouth.' The social pathology is comprehensive: the wealthy use violence to accumulate; the general population uses deception in speech. Both are covenant violations — violence against covenant (Exod 20:13; Lev 19:16) and lying against covenant (Exod 20:16; Lev 19:11). The corruption is not limited to the elite; it has permeated the entire speech-community.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Therefore I strike you with a grievous blow, making you desolate because of your sins.' The divine punishment is announced: a grievous blow (<em>hechleiti hakkotcha</em>). The root <em>chalah</em> (be sick/wounded) is used — the blow will wound gravely, perhaps mortally. This parallels 1:9 ('her wound is incurable'). The desolation (<em>shemamah</em>) is the result of the sin specifically, not arbitrary divine anger.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'You shall eat, but not be satisfied, and there shall be hunger within you; you shall put away, but not save, and what you save I will give to the sword.' The covenant curses of Deut 28:38-44 echo throughout vv. 14-15: eating without being satisfied, putting away without saving, planting without harvesting. These are the precise reversal of the covenant blessings (Deut 28:1-14: full satisfaction, secure savings, abundant harvest). The text enacts the covenant curse structure without citing it directly.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'You shall sow, but not reap; you shall tread olives, but not anoint yourselves with oil; you shall tread grapes, but not drink wine.' The agricultural futility curse (Deut 28:38-41) is spelled out for the three major Judean crops: grain, olives, grapes. The labor-without-benefit formula captures the essential character of the curse: not poverty but purposeless toil, effort that produces results which are then taken away. The triad of grain, oil, and wine appears throughout the Hebrew Bible as the symbol of the land's bounty (Deut 7:13; Joel 1:10; Hos 2:8).</p>",
    "16": "<p>'For you have kept the statutes of Omri, and all the works of the house of Ahab; and you have walked in their counsels, that I may make you a desolation, and your inhabitants a hissing; so you shall bear the scorn of my people.' Omri (885–874 BCE) and Ahab (874–853 BCE) are the arch-villains of the Deuteronomic history — their dynasty introduced Baal worship systematically into the northern kingdom (1 Kgs 16:25-26; 21). Judah has now adopted the northern kingdom's worst religious and social practices. The condemnation brings the covenant lawsuit full circle: YHWH rehearsed his faithfulness (vv. 4-5); now the specific statute-violations explain why the curses are just.</p>"
  }
}

